{"title_page": "Johnny Hotbody", "text_new": "{{short description|American professional wrestler}}\n{{Infobox professional wrestler\n|name        = Johnny Hotbody\n|birthname   = John Weiss\n|image       =\n|names       = Johnny Hotbody<ref name=\"OWOW\"/>\n|height      = {{height|ft=5|in=10}}<ref name=\"bodyslamming\">{{cite web|url=http://www.bodyslamming.com/other/hotbody.html|title=Johnny Hotbody|accessdate=2009-04-12|publisher=BodySlamming.com}}</ref>\n|weight      = {{convert|220|lb|kg|abbr=on}}<ref name=\"bodyslamming\"/>\n|birth_date  = {{Birth date and age|1963|6|12|mf=y}}\n|death_date Hotbody =\n|birth_place =\n|death_place =\n|resides     = [[Philadelphia]], [[Pennsylvania]]<ref name=\"bodyslamming\"/>\n|trainer     = [[Larry Sharpe (wrestler)|Larry Sharpe]]\n|debut       = 1988<ref name=\"bodyslamming\"/>\n|retired      =2001\n}}\n'''John Weiss''' (born February 19, 1963) is an [[United States|American]] retired [[Professional wrestling|professional wrestler]], better known by his [[ring name]] '''Johnny Hotbody'''.<ref name=\"OWOW\">{{cite web|url=http://www.onlineworldofwrestling.com/profiles/j/johnny-hotbody.html|title=Johnny Hotbody profile|accessdate=2009-04-12|publisher=Online World of Wrestling}}</ref> In [[Extreme Championship Wrestling|Eastern Championship Wrestling]], he won the ECW Championship, ECW Tag Team Championship, and ECW Television Championship.\n\n==Professional wrestling career==\n\n===Early career===\nJohnny Hotbody broke into professional wrestling in the late 1980s after completing his training at The Monster Factory, operated by [[Larry Sharpe (wrestler)|Larry Sharpe]]. He made a name for himself in several [[Pennsylvania]] and [[New Jersey]]- based independent promotions before signing with Philadelphia's [[Extreme Championship Wrestling#Tri-State Wrestling Alliance and Eastern Championship Wrestling|Tri-State Wrestling Alliance]] (TWA) in 1990. Hotbody had a long-running feud with [[Tony Stetson]]. The TWA closed its doors suddenly in 1991, but was soon replaced by [[Extreme Championship Wrestling|Eastern Championship Wrestling]] (later Extreme Championship Wrestling), run by [[Tod Gordon]].\n\n===Eastern Championship Wrestling (1992-1993)===\nOn April 26, 1992, Hotbody won the [[ECW Championship|ECW Heavyweight Championship]] by defeating [[Jimmy Snuka]].<ref name=\"OWOW\"/> He held the title for nearly three months, before losing it back to Snuka on July 14.<ref name=\"OWOW\"/> Later that year, on August 12, he became the first ever [[ECW World Television Championship|ECW Television Champion]] by defeating [[Larry Winters]].<ref name=\"OWOW\"/><ref name=\"ECWtv\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/ecw/history/ecwtvtitlehistory/|title=History of the ECW TV Championship|accessdate=2009-04-12|publisher=[[World Wrestling Entertainment]]}}</ref> He was later forced to relinquish the title on September 12, 1992, after sustaining a [[Legit (professional wrestling)|legitimate]] broken ankle.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.solie.org/titlehistories/tvecw.html|title=ECW Television Title / ECW World Television Title History|accessdate=2008-12-07|last=Duncan|first=Royal|author2=Will, Gary|work=Wrestling Title Histories|publisher=Solie's Title Histories}}</ref>\n\nUpon his return, he formed The Suicide Blondes with [[Chris Candido]], and, for most of 1993, he competed in tag team competition. He won his first [[ECW World Tag Team Championship|ECW Tag Team Championship]] with Candido on April 3, 1993, when they defeated [[Tony Stetson]] and Larry Winters.<ref name=\"OWOW\"/><ref name=\"ECWtag\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/ecw/history/ecwtaghistory/|title=History of the ECW Tag Team Championship|accessdate=2009-04-12|publisher=[[World Wrestling Entertainment]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.onlineworldofwrestling.com/results/ecw/1993.html|title=Eastern Championship Wrestling Results - May 25, 1993 -- ECW Television in Philadelphia, PA|date=1993-05-25|accessdate=2009-04-12|publisher=Online World of Wrestling}}</ref> [[Chris Michaels]] was later introduced as the third member of The Suicide Blondes, which resulted in The Suicide Blondes defending the Tag Team Championships under the [[Fabulous Freebirds#Freebird Rule|Freebird Rule]], which meant that any combination of the three were allowed to defend the championship.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.onlineworldofwrestling.com/results/ecw/1993.html|title=Eastern Championship Wrestling Results - June 8, 1993 -- ECW Television in Philadelphia, PA at ECW Arena|date=1993-06-08|accessdate=2009-04-12|publisher=Online World of Wrestling}}</ref> He also began a feud with [[Tommy Cairo]], attacking him after matches.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.onlineworldofwrestling.com/results/ecw/1993.html|title=Eastern Championship Wrestling Results - April 6, 1993 -- ECW Television in Philadelphia, PA|date=1993-04-06|accessdate=2009-04-12|publisher=Online World of Wrestling}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.onlineworldofwrestling.com/results/ecw/1993.html|title=Eastern Championship Wrestling Results - April 14, 1993 -- ECW Television in Philadelphia, PA|date=1993-04-14|accessdate=2009-04-12|publisher=Online World of Wrestling}}</ref> The Suicide Blondes defeated Cairo and [[J.T. Smith (wrestler)|J.T. Smith]] in a tag team match, and for the next few weeks Hotbody competed against Cairo in matches, losing a standard [[Professional wrestling match types#Variations of singles matches|singles match]] to him, but winning a [[Professional wrestling match types#Lumberjack match|Lumberjack match]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.onlineworldofwrestling.com/results/ecw/1993.html|title=Eastern Championship Wrestling Results - April 28, 1993--ECW Television in Philadelphia,PA|date=1993-04-28|accessdate=2009-04-12|publisher=Online World of Wrestling}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.onlineworldofwrestling.com/results/ecw/1993.html|title=Eastern Championship Wrestling Results - May 4, 1993 -- ECW Television in Philadelphia, PA|date=1993-05-04|accessdate=2009-04-12|publisher=Online World of Wrestling}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.onlineworldofwrestling.com/results/ecw/1993.html|title=Eastern Championship Wrestling Results - May 11, 1993 -- ECW Television in Philadelphia, PA|date=1993-05-11|accessdate=2009-04-12|publisher=Online World of Wrestling}}</ref> They lost the Tag Team Championship to [[The Super Destroyers]] ([[A.J. Petrucci]] and [[Doug Stahl]]) on May 15, but the combination of Hotbody and Michaels regained it that same day.<ref name=\"OWOW\"/><ref name=\"ECWtag\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.onlineworldofwrestling.com/results/ecw/1993.html|title=Eastern Championship Wrestling Results - July 20, 1993 -- ECW Television in Philadelphia, PA at ECW Arena|date=1993-07-20|accessdate=2009-04-12|publisher=Online World of Wrestling}}</ref> Later that year, on October 1, Hotbody, along with his former adversary Stetson, was awarded the Tag Team Championship, after the previous champions, [[Doug Gilbert|The Dark Patriot]] and [[Eddie Gilbert (wrestler)|Eddie Gilbert]], left the [[Professional wrestling promotion|promotion]], resulting in the titles being vacated.<ref name=\"OWOW\"/><ref name=\"ECWtag\"/> They had successful title defenses against [[Badd Company]] ([[Paul Diamond]] and [[Pat Tanaka]]), [[The Sandman (wrestler)|The Sandman]] and J.T. Smith, and [[Ian Rotten|Ian]] and [[Axl Rotten]] over the next month.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.onlineworldofwrestling.com/results/ecw/1993.html|title=Eastern Championship Wrestling Results - October 2, 1993 -- NWA Bloodfest: Part 2 in Philadelphia, Pennsylvania at ECW Arena|date=1993-10-02|accessdate=2009-04-12|publisher=Online World of Wrestling}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.onlineworldofwrestling.com/results/ecw/1993.html|title=Eastern Championship Wrestling Results - October 1, 1993 -- NWA Bloodfest: Part 1 in Philadelphia, Pennsylvania at ECW Arena|date=1993-10-01|accessdate=2009-04-12|publisher=Online World of Wrestling}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.onlineworldofwrestling.com/results/ecw/1993.html|title=Eastern Championship Wrestling Results - November 13, 1993 -- November to Remember in Philadelphia, Pennsylvania at ECW Arena:|date=1993-11-13|accessdate=2009-04-12|publisher=Online World of Wrestling}}</ref> They [[Glossary of professional wrestling terms#Drop|dropped]] the championship to [[Tommy Dreamer]] and [[Tom Brandi|Johnny Gunn]], however, in a nine-second match, on November 13.<ref name=\"ECWtag\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://slam.canoe.ca/Slam/Wrestling/Bios/dreamer_tommy.html|title=Tommy Dreamer|last=Milner|first=John M.|author2=Kapur, Bob|accessdate=2009-04-12|work=Slam! Sports|publisher=[[Canadian Online Explorer]]}}</ref>\n\n===Retirement===\nHotbody later competed for the [[National Wrestling Alliance|NWA New Jersey]], where he was awarded the [[NWA World Light Heavyweight Championship (New Jersey version)|New Jersey version of the NWA World Light Heavyweight Championship]] on September 25, 1998.<ref name=\"OWOW\"/> He lost it to [[Rik Ratchett]] that same day. After successful tours in several Philadelphia-area independent promotions, Hotbody retired from active competition in 2001.\n\n==Championships and accomplishments==\n*'''[[Extreme Championship Wrestling|Eastern Championship Wrestling]]'''\n**[[ECW World Heavyweight Championship|ECW Heavyweight Championship]] ([[List of ECW Champions|1 time]])<sup>1</sup><ref name=\"OWOW\"/>\n**[[ECW World Tag Team Championship|ECW Tag Team Championship]] ([[List of ECW World Tag Team Champions|3 times]]) - with [[Chris Candido]] and Chris Michaels (2), and Tony Stetson (1)<ref name=\"OWOW\"/><ref name=\"ECWtag\"/>\n**[[ECW World Television Championship|ECW Television Championship]] ([[List of ECW Television Champions|1 time]])<ref name=\"OWOW\"/><ref name=\"ECWtv\"/>\n*'''[[National Wrestling Alliance|NWA New Jersey]]\n**[[NWA World Light Heavyweight Championship (New Jersey version)|NWA World Light Heavyweight Champion ''(New Jersey version)'']] ([[NWA World Light Heavyweight Championship (New Jersey version)#Title history|1 time]])<ref name=\"OWOW\"/><ref name=\"bodyslamming\"/>\n*'''[[Extreme Championship Wrestling#Tri-State Wrestling Alliance and Eastern Championship Wrestling|Tri-State Wrestling Alliance]]'''\n**TWA Tag Team Championship (1 time) - with Larry Winters<ref name=\"bodyslamming\"/>\n*'''[[World Wrestling Association]]'''\n**WWA Junior Heavyweight Championship (2 times)<ref name=\"bodyslamming\"/><ref name=\"Titles\">{{cite book | author=Royal Duncan & Gary Will | title=Wrestling Title Histories | publisher=Archeus Communications | year=2000|edition=4th | isbn=0-9698161-5-4 }}</ref>\n*'''Other titles'''\n**NAWA United States Heavyweight Championship (1 time)\n\n<sup>1</sup>Johnny Hotbody's reign occurred while the promotion was an [[National Wrestling Alliance|NWA]] affiliate named [[Extreme Championship Wrestling|Eastern Championship Wrestling]], and was prior to the promotion becoming Extreme Championship Wrestling and the title being declared a world title by ECW.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.onlineworldofwrestling.com/profiles/j/johnny-hotbody.html Online World of Wrestling profile]\n*{{IMDb name|1435810}}\n\n{{ECW Championship}}\n{{ECW World Television Championship}}\n{{ECW World Tag Team Championship}}\n{{Grand Slam-Triple Crown Champions}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hotbody, Johnny}}\n[[Category:1963 births]]\n[[Category:American male professional wrestlers]]\n[[Category:ECW Heavyweight Champions/ECW World Heavyweight Champions]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:ECW World Television Champions]]\n[[Category:ECW World Tag Team Champions]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American retired professional wrestler|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{Infobox professional wrestler\n|name        = Johnny Hotbody\n|birthname   = John Weiss\n|image       =\n|names       = Johnny Hotbody<ref name=\"OWOW\"/>\n|height      = {{height|ft=5|in=10}}<ref name=\"bodyslamming\">{{cite web|url=http://www.bodyslamming.com/other/hotbody.html|title=Johnny Hotbody|accessdate=2009-04-12|publisher=BodySlamming.com}}</ref>\n|weight      = {{convert|220|lb|kg|abbr=on}}<ref name=\"bodyslamming\"/>\n|birth_date  = {{Birth date and age|1963|6|12|mf=y}}\n|death_date Hotbody =\n|birth_place =\n|death_place =\n|resides     = [[Philadelphia]], [[Pennsylvania]]<ref name=\"bodyslamming\"/>\n|trainer     = [[Larry Sharpe (wrestler)|Larry Sharpe]]\n|debut       = 1988<ref name=\"bodyslamming\"/>\n|retired      =2001\n}}\n'''John Weiss''' (born February 19, 1963) is an [[United States|American]] retired [[Professional wrestling|professional wrestler]], better known by his [[ring name]] '''Johnny Hotbody'''.<ref name=\"OWOW\">{{cite web|url=http://www.onlineworldofwrestling.com/profiles/j/johnny-hotbody.html|title=Johnny Hotbody profile|accessdate=2009-04-12|publisher=Online World of Wrestling}}</ref> In [[Extreme Championship Wrestling|Eastern Championship Wrestling]], he won the ECW Championship, ECW Tag Team Championship, and ECW Television Championship.\n\n==Professional wrestling career==\n\n===Early career===\nJohnny Hotbody broke into professional wrestling in the late 1980s after completing his training at The Monster Factory, operated by [[Larry Sharpe (wrestler)|Larry Sharpe]]. He made a name for himself in several [[Pennsylvania]] and [[New Jersey]]- based independent promotions before signing with Philadelphia's [[Extreme Championship Wrestling#Tri-State Wrestling Alliance and Eastern Championship Wrestling|Tri-State Wrestling Alliance]] (TWA) in 1990. Hotbody had a long-running feud with [[Tony Stetson]]. The TWA closed its doors suddenly in 1991, but was soon replaced by [[Extreme Championship Wrestling|Eastern Championship Wrestling]] (later Extreme Championship Wrestling), run by [[Tod Gordon]].\n\n===Eastern Championship Wrestling (1992-1993)===\nOn April 26, 1992, Hotbody won the [[ECW Championship|ECW Heavyweight Championship]] by defeating [[Jimmy Snuka]].<ref name=\"OWOW\"/> He held the title for nearly three months, before losing it back to Snuka on July 14.<ref name=\"OWOW\"/> Later that year, on August 12, he became the first ever [[ECW World Television Championship|ECW Television Champion]] by defeating [[Larry Winters]].<ref name=\"OWOW\"/><ref name=\"ECWtv\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/ecw/history/ecwtvtitlehistory/|title=History of the ECW TV Championship|accessdate=2009-04-12|publisher=[[World Wrestling Entertainment]]}}</ref> He was later forced to relinquish the title on September 12, 1992, after sustaining a [[Legit (professional wrestling)|legitimate]] broken ankle.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.solie.org/titlehistories/tvecw.html|title=ECW Television Title / ECW World Television Title History|accessdate=2008-12-07|last=Duncan|first=Royal|author2=Will, Gary|work=Wrestling Title Histories|publisher=Solie's Title Histories}}</ref>\n\nUpon his return, he formed The Suicide Blondes with [[Chris Candido]], and, for most of 1993, he competed in tag team competition. He won his first [[ECW World Tag Team Championship|ECW Tag Team Championship]] with Candido on April 3, 1993, when they defeated [[Tony Stetson]] and Larry Winters.<ref name=\"OWOW\"/><ref name=\"ECWtag\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/ecw/history/ecwtaghistory/|title=History of the ECW Tag Team Championship|accessdate=2009-04-12|publisher=[[World Wrestling Entertainment]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.onlineworldofwrestling.com/results/ecw/1993.html|title=Eastern Championship Wrestling Results - May 25, 1993 -- ECW Television in Philadelphia, PA|date=1993-05-25|accessdate=2009-04-12|publisher=Online World of Wrestling}}</ref> [[Chris Michaels]] was later introduced as the third member of The Suicide Blondes, which resulted in The Suicide Blondes defending the Tag Team Championships under the [[Fabulous Freebirds#Freebird Rule|Freebird Rule]], which meant that any combination of the three were allowed to defend the championship.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.onlineworldofwrestling.com/results/ecw/1993.html|title=Eastern Championship Wrestling Results - June 8, 1993 -- ECW Television in Philadelphia, PA at ECW Arena|date=1993-06-08|accessdate=2009-04-12|publisher=Online World of Wrestling}}</ref> He also began a feud with [[Tommy Cairo]], attacking him after matches.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.onlineworldofwrestling.com/results/ecw/1993.html|title=Eastern Championship Wrestling Results - April 6, 1993 -- ECW Television in Philadelphia, PA|date=1993-04-06|accessdate=2009-04-12|publisher=Online World of Wrestling}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.onlineworldofwrestling.com/results/ecw/1993.html|title=Eastern Championship Wrestling Results - April 14, 1993 -- ECW Television in Philadelphia, PA|date=1993-04-14|accessdate=2009-04-12|publisher=Online World of Wrestling}}</ref> The Suicide Blondes defeated Cairo and [[J.T. Smith (wrestler)|J.T. Smith]] in a tag team match, and for the next few weeks Hotbody competed against Cairo in matches, losing a standard [[Professional wrestling match types#Variations of singles matches|singles match]] to him, but winning a [[Professional wrestling match types#Lumberjack match|Lumberjack match]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.onlineworldofwrestling.com/results/ecw/1993.html|title=Eastern Championship Wrestling Results - April 28, 1993--ECW Television in Philadelphia,PA|date=1993-04-28|accessdate=2009-04-12|publisher=Online World of Wrestling}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.onlineworldofwrestling.com/results/ecw/1993.html|title=Eastern Championship Wrestling Results - May 4, 1993 -- ECW Television in Philadelphia, PA|date=1993-05-04|accessdate=2009-04-12|publisher=Online World of Wrestling}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.onlineworldofwrestling.com/results/ecw/1993.html|title=Eastern Championship Wrestling Results - May 11, 1993 -- ECW Television in Philadelphia, PA|date=1993-05-11|accessdate=2009-04-12|publisher=Online World of Wrestling}}</ref> They lost the Tag Team Championship to [[The Super Destroyers]] ([[A.J. Petrucci]] and [[Doug Stahl]]) on May 15, but the combination of Hotbody and Michaels regained it that same day.<ref name=\"OWOW\"/><ref name=\"ECWtag\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.onlineworldofwrestling.com/results/ecw/1993.html|title=Eastern Championship Wrestling Results - July 20, 1993 -- ECW Television in Philadelphia, PA at ECW Arena|date=1993-07-20|accessdate=2009-04-12|publisher=Online World of Wrestling}}</ref> Later that year, on October 1, Hotbody, along with his former adversary Stetson, was awarded the Tag Team Championship, after the previous champions, [[Doug Gilbert|The Dark Patriot]] and [[Eddie Gilbert (wrestler)|Eddie Gilbert]], left the [[Professional wrestling promotion|promotion]], resulting in the titles being vacated.<ref name=\"OWOW\"/><ref name=\"ECWtag\"/> They had successful title defenses against [[Badd Company]] ([[Paul Diamond]] and [[Pat Tanaka]]), [[The Sandman (wrestler)|The Sandman]] and J.T. Smith, and [[Ian Rotten|Ian]] and [[Axl Rotten]] over the next month.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.onlineworldofwrestling.com/results/ecw/1993.html|title=Eastern Championship Wrestling Results - October 2, 1993 -- NWA Bloodfest: Part 2 in Philadelphia, Pennsylvania at ECW Arena|date=1993-10-02|accessdate=2009-04-12|publisher=Online World of Wrestling}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.onlineworldofwrestling.com/results/ecw/1993.html|title=Eastern Championship Wrestling Results - October 1, 1993 -- NWA Bloodfest: Part 1 in Philadelphia, Pennsylvania at ECW Arena|date=1993-10-01|accessdate=2009-04-12|publisher=Online World of Wrestling}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.onlineworldofwrestling.com/results/ecw/1993.html|title=Eastern Championship Wrestling Results - November 13, 1993 -- November to Remember in Philadelphia, Pennsylvania at ECW Arena:|date=1993-11-13|accessdate=2009-04-12|publisher=Online World of Wrestling}}</ref> They [[Glossary of professional wrestling terms#Drop|dropped]] the championship to [[Tommy Dreamer]] and [[Tom Brandi|Johnny Gunn]], however, in a nine-second match, on November 13.<ref name=\"ECWtag\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://slam.canoe.ca/Slam/Wrestling/Bios/dreamer_tommy.html|title=Tommy Dreamer|last=Milner|first=John M.|author2=Kapur, Bob|accessdate=2009-04-12|work=Slam! Sports|publisher=[[Canadian Online Explorer]]}}</ref>\n\n===Retirement===\nHotbody later competed for the [[National Wrestling Alliance|NWA New Jersey]], where he was awarded the [[NWA World Light Heavyweight Championship (New Jersey version)|New Jersey version of the NWA World Light Heavyweight Championship]] on September 25, 1998.<ref name=\"OWOW\"/> He lost it to [[Rik Ratchett]] that same day. After successful tours in several Philadelphia-area independent promotions, Hotbody retired from active competition in 2001.\n\n==Championships and accomplishments==\n*'''[[Extreme Championship Wrestling|Eastern Championship Wrestling]]'''\n**[[ECW World Heavyweight Championship|ECW Heavyweight Championship]] ([[List of ECW Champions|1 time]])<sup>1</sup><ref name=\"OWOW\"/>\n**[[ECW World Tag Team Championship|ECW Tag Team Championship]] ([[List of ECW World Tag Team Champions|3 times]]) - with [[Chris Candido]] and Chris Michaels (2), and Tony Stetson (1)<ref name=\"OWOW\"/><ref name=\"ECWtag\"/>\n**[[ECW World Television Championship|ECW Television Championship]] ([[List of ECW Television Champions|1 time]])<ref name=\"OWOW\"/><ref name=\"ECWtv\"/>\n*'''[[National Wrestling Alliance|NWA New Jersey]]\n**[[NWA World Light Heavyweight Championship (New Jersey version)|NWA World Light Heavyweight Champion ''(New Jersey version)'']] ([[NWA World Light Heavyweight Championship (New Jersey version)#Title history|1 time]])<ref name=\"OWOW\"/><ref name=\"bodyslamming\"/>\n*'''[[Extreme Championship Wrestling#Tri-State Wrestling Alliance and Eastern Championship Wrestling|Tri-State Wrestling Alliance]]'''\n**TWA Tag Team Championship (1 time) - with Larry Winters<ref name=\"bodyslamming\"/>\n*'''[[World Wrestling Association]]'''\n**WWA Junior Heavyweight Championship (2 times)<ref name=\"bodyslamming\"/><ref name=\"Titles\">{{cite book | author=Royal Duncan & Gary Will | title=Wrestling Title Histories | publisher=Archeus Communications | year=2000|edition=4th | isbn=0-9698161-5-4 }}</ref>\n*'''Other titles'''\n**NAWA United States Heavyweight Championship (1 time)\n\n<sup>1</sup>Johnny Hotbody's reign occurred while the promotion was an [[National Wrestling Alliance|NWA]] affiliate named [[Extreme Championship Wrestling|Eastern Championship Wrestling]], and was prior to the promotion becoming Extreme Championship Wrestling and the title being declared a world title by ECW.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.onlineworldofwrestling.com/profiles/j/johnny-hotbody.html Online World of Wrestling profile]\n*{{IMDb name|1435810}}\n\n{{ECW Championship}}\n{{ECW World Television Championship}}\n{{ECW World Tag Team Championship}}\n{{Grand Slam-Triple Crown Champions}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hotbody, Johnny}}\n[[Category:1963 births]]\n[[Category:American male professional wrestlers]]\n[[Category:ECW Heavyweight Champions/ECW World Heavyweight Champions]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:ECW World Television Champions]]\n[[Category:ECW World Tag Team Champions]]\n", "name_user": "KC Roosters", "label": "safe", "comment": "Changingshort descriptionfrom \"American retired professional wrestler\" to \"American professional wrestler\" (Shortdesc helper)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Johnny_Hotbody"}
{"title_page": "Andy Stanley", "text_new": "{{BLP sources|date=August 2018}}\n{{Infobox clergy\n| name          = Andy Stanley\n| image         = Andy2018edit.jpg\n| caption       = Stanley in 2018\n| birth_name    = Charles Andrew Stanley\n| birth_date    = {{birth_date and age|1958|05|16}}\n| birth_place   = [[Atlanta]], [[Georgia (US state)|Georgia]], US\n| death_date    = <!-- {{death date|YD|MD|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} death date first, then birth date -->\n| death_place   = \n| religion      = Christianity ([[nondenominational Christianity|nondenominational]] [[evangelicalism|evangelical]])\n| alma_mater    = {{unbulleted list | [[Georgia State University]] | [[Dallas Theological Seminary]]}}\n| residence     = [[Milton, Georgia|Milton]], [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]], US\n| writings      = \n| congregations = [[North Point Community Church]]\n| spouse        = {{marriage|Sandra Stanley|1988}}\n| parents       = {{unbulleted list | [[Charles Stanley]] | Anna Johnson Stanley}}\n| website       = {{official URL}}\n}}\n\n'''Charles Andrew Stanley''' (born May 16, 1958), known as '''Andy Stanley''', is the senior [[pastor]] of [[North Point Community Church]], [[Buckhead Church]], [[Browns Bridge Church]], Gwinnett Church, Woodstock City Church, and Decatur City Church. He also founded North Point Ministries, which is a worldwide [[Christianity|Christian]] organization.{{citation needed|date=August 2018}}\n\n== Biography ==\n\nAndy Stanley founded Atlanta-based North Point Ministries in 1995. Today, NPM consists of seven churches in the Atlanta area and a network of more than 90 churches around the globe that collectively serve nearly 185,000 people weekly. A survey of U.S. pastors in Outreach Magazine identified Andy as one of the ten most influential living pastors in America.[https://outreachmagazine.com/interviews/21383-andy-stanley-2.html]\n\nAndy holds an undergraduate degree in journalism from Georgia State University and a master's degree from Dallas Theological Seminary. He is the author of more than 20 books, including The New Rules for Love, Sex & Dating; Ask It; How to Be Rich; Deep & Wide; Enemies of the Heart; When Work & Family Collide; Visioneering; Next Generation Leader; and Irresistible.\n\nOver 1.8 million of his messages, leadership videos, and podcasts are accessed from North Point's website monthly.\n\nYour Move with Andy Stanley premiered on NBC after Saturday Night Live in 2012 and on CBS after The Late Late Show with James Corden in 2017, giving him an even wider audience. Currently, over seven million episodes are consumed each month through television and podcasts.\n\nHe speaks at various annual events before audiences of both church and organizational leaders.\n\nAndy and his wife, Sandra, have three grown children and live near Atlanta.\n\n== Personal life ==\n\nStanley now lives in [[Milton, Georgia]], with his wife Sandra and their three adult children: Andrew, Garrett, and Allie. His father is [[Charles Stanley]], the senior pastor of the [[First Baptist Church (Atlanta)|First Baptist Church of Atlanta]] and founder of [[In Touch Ministries]].\n\n== Authored books ==\n*''Irresistible''. Zondervan, 2018. {{ISBN|978-0-310-53699-4}}.\n*''The New Rules For Love, Sex & Dating''. Zondervan, 2014. {{ISBN|978-0-310-34219-9}}.\n*''How To Be Rich''. Zondervan, 2013. {{ISBN|1624909469}}.\n*''Deep & Wide''. Zondervan, 2012. {{ISBN|0310494842}}.\n*''When Work & Family Collide''. Multnomah, 2012. {{ISBN|1601423799}}.\n*''Enemies of the Heart''. Multnomah, 2011. {{ISBN|1-60142-145-1}}.\n*''The Grace of God''. Thomas Nelson, 2010. {{ISBN|0-8499-4814-2}}.\n*''The Principle of the Path''. Thomas Nelson, 2009. {{ISBN|0-8499-2060-4}}.\n*''Communicating For a Change''. Multnomah, 2006. {{ISBN|1-59052-514-0}}.\n*''Next Generation Leader''. Multnomah, 2006. {{ISBN|1-59052-539-6}}.\n*''It Came From Within!''. Multnomah, 2006. {{ISBN|1-59052-510-8}}.\n*''Fields of Gold''. Tyndale, 2006. {{ISBN|1414311966}}.\n*''The Best Question Ever''. Multnomah, 2004. {{ISBN|1-59052-390-3}}.\n*''Seven Practices of Effective Ministry''. Multnomah, 2004. {{ISBN|1-59052-373-3}}.\n*''Creating Community''. Multnomah, 2004. {{ISBN|1-59052-396-2}}.\n*''Louder Than Words''. Multnomah, 2004. {{ISBN|1-59052-346-6}}.\n*''Can We Do That? Innovative Practices that will Change the Way You Do Church ''(With [[Ed Young Jr.]]). Howard Books, 2004''. ''{{ISBN|1582294577}}.\n* ''How Good Is Good Enough?''. Multnomah, 2003. {{ISBN|1-59052-401-2}}.\n*''Choosing To Cheat''. Multnomah, 2002. {{ISBN|1-59052-329-6}}.\n*''The Seven Checkpoints: Student Journal''. Howard Books 2001. {{ISBN|1-58229-178-0}}.\n*''Visioneering''. Multnomah, 1998. {{ISBN|1-57673-787-X}}.\n*''Like a Rock''. Thomas Nelson, 1997. {{ISBN|0-7852-7612-2}}.\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Official website}}\n* [http://northpointministries.org North Point Ministries]\n\n{{Portal bar|Biography|Christianity}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Stanley, Andy}}\n[[Category:1958 births]]\n[[Category:20th-century Baptist ministers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American male writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century Baptist ministers]]\n[[Category:American Christian writers]]\n[[Category:American evangelicals]]\n[[Category:American male non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:Baptists from Georgia (U.S. state)]]\n[[Category:Baptist ministers from the United States]]\n[[Category:Baptist writers]]\n[[Category:Dallas Theological Seminary alumni]]\n[[Category:Georgia State University alumni]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Alpharetta, Georgia]]\n", "text_old": "{{BLP sources|date=August 2018}}\n{{Infobox clergy\n| name          = Andy Stanley\n| image         = Andy2018edit.jpg\n| caption       = Stanley in 2018\n| birth_name    = Charles Andrew Stanley\n| birth_date    = {{birth_date and age|1958|05|16}}\n| birth_place   = [[Atlanta]], [[Georgia (US state)|Georgia]], US\n| death_date    = <!-- {{death date|YD|MD|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} death date first, then birth date -->\n| death_place   = \n| religion      = Christianity ([[nondenominational Christianity|nondenominational]] [[evangelicalism|evangelical]])\n| alma_mater    = {{unbulleted list | [[Georgia State University]] | [[Dallas Theological Seminary]]}}\n| residence     = [[Milton, Georgia|Milton]], [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]], US\n| writings      = \n| congregations = [[North Point Community Church]]\n| spouse        = {{marriage|Sandra Stanley|1988}}\n| parents       = {{unbulleted list | [[Charles Stanley]] | Anna Johnson Stanley}}\n| website       = {{official URL}}\n}}\n\n'''Charles Andrew Stanley''' (born May 16, 1958), known as '''Andy Stanley''', is the senior [[pastor]] of [[North Point Community Church]], [[Buckhead Church]], [[Browns Bridge Church]], Gwinnett Church, Woodstock City Church, and Decatur City Church. He also founded North Point Ministries, which is a worldwide [[Christianity|Christian]] organization.{{citation needed|date=August 2018}}\n\n== Biography ==\n\nAndy Stanley founded Atlanta-based North Point Ministries in 1995. Today, NPM consists of seven churches in the Atlanta area and a network of more than 90 churches around the globe that collectively serve nearly 185,000 people weekly. A survey of U.S. pastors in Outreach Magazine identified Andy as one of the ten most influential living pastors in America.[citation needed]\n\nAndy holds an undergraduate degree in journalism from Georgia State University and a master's degree from Dallas Theological Seminary. He is the author of more than 20 books, including The New Rules for Love, Sex & Dating; Ask It; How to Be Rich; Deep & Wide; Enemies of the Heart; When Work & Family Collide; Visioneering; Next Generation Leader; and Irresistible.\n\nOver 1.8 million of his messages, leadership videos, and podcasts are accessed from North Point's website monthly.\n\nYour Move with Andy Stanley premiered on NBC after Saturday Night Live in 2012 and on CBS after The Late Late Show with James Corden in 2017, giving him an even wider audience. Currently, over seven million episodes are consumed each month through television and podcasts.\n\nHe speaks at various annual events before audiences of both church and organizational leaders.\n\nAndy and his wife, Sandra, have three grown children and live near Atlanta.\n\n== Personal life ==\n\nStanley now lives in [[Milton, Georgia]], with his wife Sandra and their three adult children: Andrew, Garrett, and Allie. His father is [[Charles Stanley]], the senior pastor of the [[First Baptist Church (Atlanta)|First Baptist Church of Atlanta]] and founder of [[In Touch Ministries]].\n\n== Authored books ==\n*''Irresistible''. Zondervan, 2018. {{ISBN|978-0-310-53699-4}}.\n*''The New Rules For Love, Sex & Dating''. Zondervan, 2014. {{ISBN|978-0-310-34219-9}}.\n*''How To Be Rich''. Zondervan, 2013. {{ISBN|1624909469}}.\n*''Deep & Wide''. Zondervan, 2012. {{ISBN|0310494842}}.\n*''When Work & Family Collide''. Multnomah, 2012. {{ISBN|1601423799}}.\n*''Enemies of the Heart''. Multnomah, 2011. {{ISBN|1-60142-145-1}}.\n*''The Grace of God''. Thomas Nelson, 2010. {{ISBN|0-8499-4814-2}}.\n*''The Principle of the Path''. Thomas Nelson, 2009. {{ISBN|0-8499-2060-4}}.\n*''Communicating For a Change''. Multnomah, 2006. {{ISBN|1-59052-514-0}}.\n*''Next Generation Leader''. Multnomah, 2006. {{ISBN|1-59052-539-6}}.\n*''It Came From Within!''. Multnomah, 2006. {{ISBN|1-59052-510-8}}.\n*''Fields of Gold''. Tyndale, 2006. {{ISBN|1414311966}}.\n*''The Best Question Ever''. Multnomah, 2004. {{ISBN|1-59052-390-3}}.\n*''Seven Practices of Effective Ministry''. Multnomah, 2004. {{ISBN|1-59052-373-3}}.\n*''Creating Community''. Multnomah, 2004. {{ISBN|1-59052-396-2}}.\n*''Louder Than Words''. Multnomah, 2004. {{ISBN|1-59052-346-6}}.\n*''Can We Do That? Innovative Practices that will Change the Way You Do Church ''(With [[Ed Young Jr.]]). Howard Books, 2004''. ''{{I